      "text": "<i>People talking about API design: zillions of good discussions online, papers written, standards created, thousands of hours of talks at dev conferences, heated debates that nearly venture into philosophy.<p>People implementing APIs: return a 200 response for everything, even an error ¯\\_(ツ)_&#x2F;¯</i><p>Those two are not contradictory; the latter <i>is</i> firmly on the side of the debate which treats HTTP strictly as transport, and considers mapping RPC errors to HTTP errors as a layering violation, inviting ambiguity and semantic mismatches. FWIW, I also subscribe to that view for RPC-shaped requests. If you receive a 200, you know that the request went through to the API server, and didn&#x27;t become sidetracked on the HTTP level."
