      "text": "For the classic HP RPN, it isn&#x27;t. Numbers are entered directly into the X register. ENTER does several things: it finishes the input, copies the new value in X to Y (shifting the rest up) and inhibits &quot;stack lift&quot;, so the stack won&#x27;t be automatically shifted up when you start entering the next number.<p>Sounds complicated, but in practice you don&#x27;t think about it at all."
